Messaging Experiment

CoreyJackson

11/24/2016

The analysis for the messaging experiment. On October 12th 2016 four types of messages were sent to users with registered accounts highlighting one of four motivational aspects of participation - altrusim, learning, contribution, and social proof (Table below). Overall, the message response Volunteers who received the altruism message were less likely to click the link to Gravity Spy than those who received other messages at significance p = .05 level; but no statistically significant difference was found among the other three message conditions. The analysis below examines the long-term impacts of the messaging on the number of classifications volunteers contributed one day, two days, one week, and one month (only data until Oct 20th) after the messages were sent.

Table 1. Four messages and the number of user accounts receiving each message. Assignment

Since the data are non-normal, the experiment was analyzed using the non-parametric Kruskal Wallis One Way Anova by Ranks Test.

Some features of the data:

  • Users who contributed prior to the experiment messaging were removed

The amount of annotations submitted between 2016-10-12 and 2016-10-13

Overall Findings

  • Impact of Messaging on getting people to contribute more annotations
    • There are no significant differences in annotations submitted during any time frame.
